CONTAMINATED BEACHES, WARNING (02)
**********************************
Date: Fri, 11 July 1997 15:50:43 MDT
From: Robert A. LaBudde <ral@lcfltd.com>
[see
Contaminated beaches, warning 970703144142]
[After posting a news item about National Resource Defense Council's [NRDC]
warnings about risk of illness at eastern US beaches, I received the
following email, which elaborates on the problem. -- RAL]
"I have been trying to get someone at the NRDF to look at some new studies.
We have found that swimming in waters that currently meet USEPA [U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency] criteria can cause gastroenteritis, acute
febrile respiratory illness, and ear problems.
We conducted 4 randomized trials, the results of which were published
in the Lancet and the AJPH [American Journal of Public Health] (non-enteric
illnesses). We are in the process of publishing estimates of severity and
have a method to calculated overall disease burden at any beach. We are
talking about an average illness period of 3 to 4 or 5 days, depending on
symptoms, and about 20% of our volunteers needing to visit a physician.
I am contacted about once a year by [name deleted -- Mod CHC], or [by] an
intern, but nothing ever comes of it.
We have the data to prove illness is occurring, USEPA criteria are not
epidemiologically sound, [we] can predict illness burdens, [make] estimates
of illness severity, and [have] enough evidence to challenge the USEPA and
the [individual] States.
The WHO is in the process of adopting our work to be used as recommended
criteria, the EC [European Community] is taking a hard look at our data,
while the US does nothing.
Both [our studies] were randomized trials. I can give you about a dozen more
that Dr. Kay and I published. We are submitting a paper on severity of the
illnesses we found this week. I cannot go public with the results, but I can
say we are talking about an average of 3-5 days of lost daily activities
among about 10% to 20% of those becomming ill, depending on the illness.
These numbers add up to an enormous disease burden when multipled by the
number of bathers going into marine waters each year.
References
Fleisher JM, Kay D, et al. Marine waters contaminated with Domestic Sewage:
Nonenteric Illness Associated with Bather exposure in the United Kingdom. Am
J Public Health, 1996, 86:1228-1234
Kay D, Fleisher JM, et al. Predicting the Likelihood of Gastroenteritis from
Sea Bathing: Results from randomized Exposure. Lancet 1994: 344:905-909.
Jay M. Fleisher Ph.D.
Department of Preventive Medicine
SUNY Health Science Center at Brooklyn
TELEPHONE 718-270-1075 FAX 718-270-2533
WEB http://www.netcom.com/~fleishe1"
e-mail: <fleishe1@ix.netcom.com>
---
Robert A. LaBudde, PhD, PAS, Dpl. ACAFS
Least Cost Formulations, Ltd.
824 Timberlake Drive
Virginia Beach, VA 23464-3239
TEL: (757) 467-0954
